<br>
but PST, grrrr. 2 times I see it used.<br>
<br>
/ooc 45 cleric lfg, pst<br>
/auc WTS LSoEE. pst.<br>
<br>
First off PST = Pacific Standard Time.<br>
<br>
I can see this happening. <br>
<br>
-So what time does the raid start?<br>
-6pm PST<br>
-I just sent you a tell<br>
-Not Please send tell, pst.<br>
-I don't follow<br>
-/sigh<br>
<br>
Secondly people use it in situations where it should be obvious. You are lfg, of course they will send a tell if they want you, if they say come to &quot;suchandsuch camp&quot;  in ooc, then oh well, not a big problem unless /ooc is off i guess<br>
<br>
secondly, if you are selling something, or buying something, most likely you will send or receive tells, if the person tries to ask in /ooc and you don't like it, then don't answer.<br>
<br>
If you HAVE to remind people to send you a tell. Simply add on &quot;Send tells&quot;. Saying please sounds like you are pleading with people to either group you or buy/sell to you IMO.<br>
<br>
Don't know why it bugs the @#%$ out of me, but it does, and I am not alone <p><p ALIGN=CENTER><a href="http://ddl.dyc.edu/~felix/tests/thug-life.htm" target="_blank"><img src="http://ddl.dyc.edu/~felix/tests/thug-life.jpg" alt="I am 3% thug-life"></a></p>
